CHAPTER 8: COMPROMISED
COLE
Nine AM. All three of them at the safehouse.
Mat arrived first. Looks like he didn't sleep. Eyes red. Wired.
Ray second. Worse than yesterday. Five days sober and his body's screaming for alcohol. Hands shaking. Sweat on his forehead despite the cool morning.
Cole's been up all night. Again. Coffee and cigarettes. His two food groups.
They stand around the table. Nobody sits. Too tense.
"Ray got a call last night," Cole says. "Blocked number. Someone threatened him."
Mat looks at Ray. "Threatened him how?"
"Said they know I was at the storage unit Thursday," Ray says. Voice rough. "Said they know I've been watching La Mer. Told me to stop or I'd have an accident."
"Fuck." Mat runs his hand through his hair. "They're onto us."
"Question is: how?" Cole lights a cigarette.
"Security footage," Ray says. "Has to be. The storage facility had cameras."
"We were masked. Gloves. Dark. They couldn't ID us."
"Unless someone ran facial recognition," Mat says. "Or tracked our cars."
"My car's registered under a shell company," Cole says. "Ray's is old, no GPS. Yours?"
"Fifteen-year-old Honda. Nothing fancy."
"Then how?" Ray asks.
Silence. All three of them thinking. Processing.
Mat speaks first. "What if it's not footage? What if someone talked?"
"Who?" Cole looks at him. "We're the only three who know."
"Cisco knows I hit something. Doesn't know details, but he knows."
"Would he talk?"
"Not to Vincent directly." Mat shakes his head. "But if Vincent's people came asking questions in the neighborhood..." He trails off. "Cisco protects his crew first. Always."
Ray leans against the wall. "Or it's simpler than that. Delgado's guys. They didn't see our faces, but they saw how we moved. How we fought. Someone with experience could narrow it down."
"To what?" Cole asks. "Three guys in LA who know how to fight?"
"To three guys who know how to fight AND have a reason to hit Vincent's network." Ray looks at Cole. "You work for him. If Vincent's paranoid, he's looking at everyone on his payroll."
Cole goes cold. "He's auditing his people."
"What?" Mat asks.
"Vincent's smart. Someone hit him. He doesn't know who. So he audits everyone who has access. Financial records. Communications. Movements. If he's looking at me—" Cole stops. "Fuck."
"What?" Ray pushes off the wall.
"I've been skimming. Using his money to fund this. If he audits my accounts—"
"He'll see the missing money," Mat finishes.
"And he'll know."
The panic sets in. Visible. All three of them realize what this means.
"How long before he figures it out?" Ray asks.
"Could be already looking. Could be days. I don't know."
"So what do we do?" Mat's voice rises slightly. "Because if Vincent knows, my family's—"
"I know." Cole cuts him off. Not angry. Just tired. "We have three options. One: abort. Disappear. Run."
"Vincent will find us," Ray says flatly.
"Two: accelerate. Hit La Mer tonight instead of Friday. Before Vincent's ready."
"We're not ready either," Mat says. "We don't have a solid plan. We don't have tech support. We don't have—"
"Three: continue as planned. Friday night. But assume Vincent knows and prepare accordingly."
Silence.
Mat speaks first. "I vote abort. Too dangerous. My family's at risk. Cisco's already suspicious. Now Vincent might know about Cole? We're fucked."
"We're fucked either way," Ray says. "Vincent suspects Cole, Cole's dead whether we do the job or not. Might as well go down fighting."
"Easy for you to say," Mat snaps. "You got nothing to lose."
Ray's face hardens. "Exactly."
Cole steps between them. "Stop. Both of you." He looks at Mat. "If we abort, Vincent still audits me. Still finds the money. Still kills me. And then he looks at who I've been talking to. And he finds you. And Ray. And your families."
Mat goes quiet.
"If we accelerate," Cole continues, "we're unprepared. Higher chance of failure. Failure means death."
"And if we continue with Friday?" Ray asks.
"We assume Vincent knows. Heavy security. Expect the worst. But we have three more days to plan. Three days to find tech support. Three days to prepare for every contingency."
"That's insane," Mat says.
"Yeah." Cole crushes out his cigarette. "But it's the only option that gives us a chance."
Long silence.
"I need to move my family," Mat says finally. "Get them out of the neighborhood before this goes down."
"Do it," Cole says. "Ray, I need you to dig into Vincent's security. Find out who called you. How they're tracking us."
Ray nods.
"And I need to find us tech support," Cole says. "Someone who can handle cameras, alarms, digital security. We've got three days."
"Where do we find someone like that?" Mat asks.
"I don't know." Cole lights another cigarette. "But without tech support, this job's impossible."
They break up. Mat leaves first. Ray second.
Cole stands alone in the safehouse. Stares at his wall of evidence.
Three days.
Vincent's closing in. Cisco's investigating. Professional surveillance watching them.
And they're going to rob a senator in a restaurant full of witnesses.
Cole almost laughs.
They're completely insane.

COLE
Tuesday afternoon. Brennan Property Solutions.
Cole sits at his desk. Acting normal. Answering emails. Processing transactions. The performance of a man who isn't planning to rob his boss in three days.
Jennifer pokes her head in. "Cole? You have a call. Line two."
"Who is it?"
"Didn't say. Just said it's important."
Cole picks up. "Brennan."
"Mr. Brennan." The voice is professional. Cold. Cole recognizes it. Vincent's lawyer.
"Yes?"
"Mr. Harlan would like to meet with you. Thursday afternoon. His office."
Cole's heart sinks. Keeps his voice steady. "About what?"
"A review of recent transactions. Routine audit."
Routine. Right.
"Of course. What time?"
"Two PM. Don't be late."
The line goes dead.
Cole sits there. Phone in his hand.
Thursday. Two PM. One day before the heist.
Vincent's calling him in for an audit.
This is it. Vincent suspects something.
Cole has two choices. Go to the meeting—might be a trap, might get killed. Or don't go—confirms guilt, Vincent comes after him immediately.
Either way, the clock is ticking.
Cole texts Ray and Mat: Vincent wants to meet me Thursday. 2 PM. Audit. This might be it.
Ray responds first: Fuck.
Mat second: You going?
Cole: Don't have a choice. If I don't go, he knows I'm guilty.
Ray: If you do go, he might kill you anyway.
Cole: Yeah.
Cole sets down his phone. Stares at his computer screen. Financial transactions. Property records. Six years of building Vincent's empire.
And now Vincent's going to ask him why he's been stealing.
Cole lights a cigarette even though Jennifer hates it.
Thursday afternoon. Thirty hours from now.
If Cole walks into that meeting, he might not walk out.
But if he doesn't go, Vincent sends people to find him.
Either way, Friday night is Cole's last chance.
Hit Vincent before Vincent hits him.

RAY
Tuesday evening. Ray's apartment.
Ray's on his couch. Phone in his hand. Obsessing over the call from last night.
Blocked number. Professional. Calm. We know.
There are ways to track blocked calls. Old cop tricks. Ray learned them during his years on the force. Before everything went to shit.
He dials a number he hasn't called in three years.
It rings. And rings.
"Yeah?" Male voice. Cautious.
"Danny. It's Ray."
Long pause. "Ray? Jesus Christ, I thought you were dead."
"Not yet." Ray's hands shake. "I need a favor."
"I don't do favors anymore, Ray. Especially not for—"
"I need a number traced. Blocked call from last night."
"Are you serious? You know what happened last time I helped you—"
"I know. And I'm sorry. But I need this, Danny. Please."
Silence. Then: "...Give me the time stamp."
Ray does. Danny's still there. Still listening.
"I'll call you back in an hour. But after this? We're done. Don't call me again."
The line goes dead.
Ray sets down his phone. Stands. Paces.
The bottle's still on the table. Cap off. Has been for two days. Open. Tempting. Right there.
Six days sober.
One hundred forty-four hours without a drink.
Ray walks past the bottle. Doesn't touch it.
But he wants to.
God, he wants to.
An hour later, his phone rings. Danny.
"Got something," Danny says. No greeting. All business. "Number's registered to a private security firm. Sterling Security Solutions."
"Vincent Harlan's people?"
"Don't know. Don't want to know." Danny's voice is hard. "We're even now, Ray. Lose my number."
He hangs up.
Ray sits down. Opens his laptop. Searches: Sterling Security Solutions.
The website loads. Professional. Clean. Corporate.
Sterling Security Solutions: Executive Protection. Risk Management. Discrete Services for High-Profile Clients.
Translation: mercenaries for rich criminals.
Ray clicks through. Services. Personnel. Contact.
He recognizes some of the names. Former military. Former CIA. The kind of people who don't ask questions and don't leave witnesses.
Vincent's using professionals.
Not street thugs. Not corrupt cops. Trained operators.
The crew is being watched by people who know what they're doing.
Ray texts Cole and Mat: The call came from Sterling Security. Vincent's using PMCs. Professional surveillance. We're being watched right now.
Cole responds: How close?
Ray: Close enough to know where I've been. Close enough to threaten me. We're burned.
Mat: Jesus Christ.
Ray sets down his phone. Looks at the bottle.
Six days sober.
But the stress is crushing him. The fear. The shaking. The voice in his head screaming for just one drink.
Ray picks up the bottle.
Holds it.
Stares at it.
Doesn't drink.
Not yet.
But the temptation is stronger every hour.
And Ray doesn't know how much longer he can hold on.

MAT
Tuesday night. Mat's apartment.
Dinner. Rosa made arroz con pollo. Isa's helping clean up. Normal. Routine.
But Mat can't focus.
He keeps checking his phone. Keeps looking out the window. Paranoid.
Professional surveillance. Sterling Security. Vincent's people are watching.
Are they watching HIM? Are they watching his building? His family?
"Mateo." Isa's voice cuts through his thoughts. She's speaking Spanish. "What's wrong?"
"Nothing. Just work stuff."
"You keep looking out the window. Like someone's following you."
"I'm fine, Isa."
She doesn't believe him. Mat can see it in her face. But Rosa's there, so Isa doesn't push.
Rosa finishes her coffee. Checks the time. "I need to go, mijos. (Sons.) Night shift."
She kisses Mat's forehead. "Be good. Love you."
"Love you too, Ma."
Rosa leaves. The door closes.
Mat and Isa sit in silence for exactly ten seconds.
"You're scaring me," Isa says quietly.
"I'm sorry."
"Whatever you're doing... is it worth it? Worth risking everything?"
Mat looks at the bills on the table. Medical bills. Rent notices. Eviction threats they barely avoided. Their run-down apartment. Rosa working two jobs and still rationing her insulin.
"I don't know anymore," Mat says honestly.
Isa reaches across the table. Takes his hand. "Then stop. Whatever it is, just stop."
"I can't."
"Why not?"
"Because I'm already in. And the only way out is through."
Isa pulls her hand back. "That's what Dad said. Right before they killed him."
The words hit hard. Mat doesn't respond.
Isa stands. Goes to her room. Closes the door.
Mat sits alone at the table.
His phone buzzes. Cole: Vincent wants to meet me Thursday. This might be it.
Then Ray: Sterling Security. Professional surveillance.
Mat's blood runs cold.
Professional surveillance means they're tracking movements. Phones. Maybe even listening.
If they're tracking Mat, they know where he lives.
Which means Rosa and Isa are in danger.
Mat makes a decision.
He pulls out his phone. Calls his cousin in Riverside. Miguel. Haven't talked to him in two years.
"Mateo? Ese, what's up?"
"Miguel, I need a favor. A big one."
"Talk."
"I need you to take in Ma and Isa for a week. Maybe two. Don't ask questions. Just keep them safe."
Silence. Then: "You in trouble, primo?" (Cousin.)
"Yeah."
"Bad trouble?"
"The worst."
"...When?"
"Tomorrow. I'll bring them tomorrow night."
"Okay. But Mat? Whatever you're into—"
"I know. I'll explain later. Just keep them safe."
"I will."
Mat hangs up.
Tomorrow night he'll move them. Get them out of the neighborhood. Away from Cisco's territory. Away from Vincent's surveillance.
At least if everything goes wrong Friday, Rosa and Isa will be safe.
Mat takes off Ricardo's watch. Stares at it.
His father promised to teach him to drive stick in the Mustang. Promised to take him to Mexico. The long ride.
They never got that ride.
Because the system killed Ricardo.
And now Mat's trying to kill the system back.
He doesn't know if it's brave or stupid.
Probably both.
Mat puts the watch back on. Feels the weight.
"Sorry, Dad," he whispers. "But I can't be clean anymore. Clean didn't save you. And it won't save us."

VINCENT
Tuesday night. Vincent's office.
Late. Quiet. Just Vincent and his computer.
He's reviewing financial records. Cole Brennan's transactions over the last six months.
Property purchases. Wire transfers. Invoices. Everything Cole's processed for Vincent's network.
The numbers are good. Clean. Professional.
But something's off.
Vincent's spent twenty years building this empire. He knows his numbers. Knows when something doesn't add up.
He opens a detailed analysis. Cross-references accounts. Compares expected amounts to actual amounts.
There.
Small discrepancies. $500 here. $1,000 there. Spread across forty transactions over three weeks.
Total: $47,000.
Not enough to be obvious. But Vincent notices everything.
Cole's been skimming.
Vincent leans back in his chair. Thinks.
Cole's been good for six years. Never skimmed before. Never stepped out of line. Model employee, if you can call a blackmailed money launderer an employee.
So why now?
Two possibilities.
One: Cole's desperate. Family problems. Debt. Medical bills. Something personal.
Two: Cole's planning something.
Vincent checks the timeline.
Skimming started three weeks ago.
Delgado was hit four days ago.
The timing is suspicious.
Vincent picks up his phone. Calls Sterling Security.
"Status on the surveillance?"
"Sir." Professional voice. Efficient. "We've identified three suspects. Still gathering intel."
"How long?"
"Two more days for confirmation."
"You have one day. I want names by Wednesday night."
"Understood."
Vincent hangs up. Makes another call. His head of security.
"Cole Brennan. I want everything. Where he lives, who he talks to, where he goes. And I want to know if he's been in contact with anyone unusual."
"Yes, sir. When do you need this?"
"Before Thursday's meeting."
"Understood."
Vincent hangs up.
Sits in silence.
Thursday's meeting is a test.
If Cole's innocent, he'll have an explanation for the missing money. Gambling. Divorce. Medical bills. Something believable.
If Cole's guilty, he'll lie.
And Vincent will know.
He's dealt with enough liars to recognize the signs.
Vincent opens a file on his computer. Document titled: "Liabilities."
A list of names. People who betrayed him over twenty years. Each name has a date next to it. The day they died.
All crossed out.
Vincent adds a new line at the bottom.
Cole Brennan - pending.
He saves the file. Closes the laptop.
No rage. No panic. Just cold calculation.
If Cole's betrayed him, Vincent will know by Thursday.
And if he has?
Well.
Vincent's dealt with traitors before.

COLE
Tuesday night. Cole's safehouse.
Cole reads the texts on his phone.
Ray: Sterling Security. Professional surveillance.
Mat: Moving my family tomorrow. Getting them out.
And Cole's own text to them: Vincent wants to meet me Thursday. 2 PM. This might be it.
Cole sets down his phone. Stares at his wall.
La Mer floor plans. Vincent's network. Senator Castellano's photo. Red string connecting everything like a conspiracy theorist's fever dream.
They're out of time.
Vincent suspects him. Professional surveillance is tracking them. Cisco's investigating Mat. The crew's compromised from every angle.
They should abort.
Run. Disappear. Try to survive.
But if they abort, Vincent still audits Cole. Still finds the missing money. Still kills him.
And then Vincent looks at who Cole's been talking to. Finds Ray. Finds Mat. Finds their families.
Running doesn't save them.
It just delays the inevitable.
The only way forward is through.
Friday night. La Mer. The senator.
Succeed or die trying.
Cole texts Mat and Ray: We're going through with it. Friday night. No matter what. If Vincent wants me dead, I'm taking his empire with me.
Mat responds: You're insane.
Ray responds: We're all insane. That's why this might actually work.
Cole almost smiles.
Three broken people. Professional surveillance. Vincent closing in. And they're going to rob his senator in his restaurant in front of a hundred witnesses.
One day before that, Cole has to walk into Vincent's office and convince him he's not a traitor.
While being a traitor.
Cole lights a cigarette. Stares at the wall.
"Yeah," he says to the empty room. "We're definitely insane."
The clock on the wall reads 11:47 PM.
Thursday meeting: thirty-eight hours.
Friday heist: eighty-six hours.
Cole doesn't sleep.
Just sits in the dark.
Smoking.
Planning.
Waiting.
